Ames Housing Model Analysis, Part 1

Steven Slezak

31 March 2018

1 Initial Preparation of the Data Sets

Our analysis of 10 different ML methods applied to the Ames housing data is divided into two parts. The first section deals with developing the benchmark model, multilinear regression. It also includes first efforts at feature selection and feature importance. The second part of the analysis examines other model methods and different approaches to feature selection.

The two parts structure the Ames data differently. To start, we are trying to develop a base model for submission to Kaggle. This requires working with the train.csv and test.csv files from Kaggle’s House Prices: Advanced Regression Techniques competition.

To start, we need to load the required libraries.

2 Checking for Collinearity

We need to look for correlations between the numeric values to check for redundancy. We will perform a Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) analysis to identify any multicollinearity in the data.

CorTable <- cor(Filter(is.numeric, AmesTr))
corrplot::corrplot(CorTable, type = 'lower')

numerics <- Filter(is.numeric, AmesTr)
usdm::vif(numerics)

The high values associated with Basement features indicate collinearity exists there, so we need to make sure not to include more than one Basement feature in the model. In addition, features related to the square footage of living space are showing Infinite VIF scores, which means the data may have some problems associated with high dimensionality. We will discuss this more in a bit.

6 Linear Model with Interaction Terms

Some feature engineering in the form of feature interaction is worth exploring. In feature interaction, variables are combined by multiplication. A number of different combinations were tried in order to find one that might provide an adjusted R2 comparable to the benchmark and which might further reduce the number of features in the regression model.

The best combination is reproduced below. It yields an adjusted R2 of 78.4 with just four features. These four features use seven from the original multilinear regression model.

Interaction permits use of a much simpler model, though one with less model accuracy. The trade-off is to be expected.

lm.fit.interactive <- lm(formula = SalePrice ~ GrLivArea + TotalBsmtSF + YearBuilt * 
                                 Neighborhood_NridgHt + 
                                 SaleType_New * Neighborhood_StoneBr * LotArea, 
                                 data = AmesTrainShort)

7 Working with Many Dimensions

The Ames data set has over 80 dimensions in its original form. Creating dummy variables increases dimensions to over 300. Though Ames is not considered a high-dimensional problem, because in Ames the n (the number of observations) is larger than p (the number of features), it still exhibits some challenges associated with high dimensionaltiy. In general, supervised learning problems can exhibit similar challenges, so it is helpful to mention them.

The curse of dimensionality describes the idea that more features do not necessarily improve goodness of fit. Using too many features, especially without adjusting for collinearity, can result in overfitting the model. An overfitted model does not scale well. It might explain a given data set well, but it cannot be applied to any other data set reliably.

Many statistical methods, such as least squares, logistic regression, and linear discriminant analysis, are not appropriate for high dimensional problems. Symptoms to watch for are a near-perfect fit and residuals approachings zero. Another symptom is variances approaching zero. During the analysis of the Ames data, R threw a number of warnings about these conditions.

Some of the features, such as those related to fireplaces, have far fewer obervations than the number of features. That is n << p. So certain features of Ames exhibits characteristics of high dimensional data.

It is important to use a number of statistical approaches to assess situations like these. Methods such as stepwise selection, ridge regression, the lasso, and principle components regression can work better in high dimensional problems.

8 Other Methods of Feature Selection

We can use regression methods to peform feature selection. The best subset selection approach identifies the best model given a certain number of features. In our case, we will work with the 16 features derived from the top 25 identified by the linear regression model. In best subset selection, the Residual Sum of Squares (RSS) is used to select and order features.

The table below indicates each variable’s importance to models of different sizes. For example, the GrLivArea is identified as the best feature to use when building a single feature model. A two-feature model would consist of GrLivArea and Year Built, and so on for more sophisticated models. A feature’s rank in importance is indicated by the first asterisk that appears in that feature’s column.

A table at the end of this document will summarize the different features and their rank using the four methods described in the study, plus boosting.

The cumulative adjusted R2 is given in the last line of the output.

Finally, it is possible to accomplish feature selection using stepwise selection. In forward stepwise selection, the model starts with a single feature, then adds features one at at time. Accuracy is measured at each step and the process ends when accuracy no longer improves with each feature added. In backward stepwise selection, the process begins with all features, which are then removed one at a time. Accuracy is tracked by measuring how much it decreases with each feature removed. The process ends when no more features can be deleted without a significant loss of fit.

We will start with forward selection. As before, the table indicates the relative importance of each factor to models of different sizes.
